<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="chp3sec2" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Uniqueness of Prime Factorization</title>

  <p> </p>

<proposition xml:id="proposition-euclid_lemma">
  <title>Euclid's Lemma</title>
  <statement>
    <p>
      If <m>p\in \Z</m> is prime and <m>p \mid bc</m> for some <m>b,c \in \Z</m>, then <m>p \mid b</m> or <m>p \mid c</m>.
    </p>
  </statement>
  <proof>
    <p>
      Try a direct proof.  Suppose <m>p \nmid b</m>.  The <m>\gcd(p,b)=1</m> (why???).  Deduce that there exist integers <m>x,y\in \Z</m> such that <m>px+by=1</m>.  Use this to show that <m>p \mid c</m>.  You may find  <xref ref="definition-prime_number"/>, <xref ref="definition-gcd"/>, <xref ref="definition-divisibility"/>, <xref ref="proposition-bezout_identity"/> and <xref ref="proposition-divisibility_of_linear_combination"/> useful.
    </p>
  </proof>
</proposition>



<p>
  The property stated in Euclid's Lemma is not just a consequence of the definition of prime numbers; it is a deeper property that distinguishes prime numbers from composite numbers.  In fact, the converse of Euclid's Lemma is also true.
</p>

<proposition xml:id="proposition-euclid_converse">
  <title>Euclid's Converse</title>
  <statement>
    <p>
      If <m>a\in \Z</m> is a number greater than 1 with the property that whenever <m>a \mid bc</m> for some <m>b,c \in \Z</m>, then <m>a \mid b</m> or <m>a \mid c</m>, then <m>a</m> is prime.
    </p>
  </statement>
  <proof>
    <p>
      Try a direct proof.  Suppose <m>d \mid a</m>.  Then there exists a <m>q\in \Z</m> such that <m>a=dq</m>.  Either <m>a \mid d</m> or <m>a \mid q</m>. Analyze both cases and deduce that <m>d</m> must either be 1 or <m>a</m>.  You may find <xref ref="definition-divisibility"/>,  <xref ref="proposition-positive_numbers_dividing_each_other_are_equal"/>, and  <xref ref="definition-prime_number"/> useful.
    </p>
  </proof>
</proposition>


<p>
  Euclid's Lemma (<xref ref="proposition-euclid_lemma"/>)is a fundamental property of prime numbers that plays a crucial role in number theory, particularly in the proof of the uniqueness of prime factorization.
</p>


<proposition xml:id="proposition-uniqueness_of_prime_factorization">
  <title>Prime Factorization (Uniqueness)</title>
  <statement>
    <p>
      The prime factorization of a positive integer greater than 1 is unique up to the order of the factors.
    </p>
  </statement>
  <proof>
    <p>
      Suppose that a positive integer <m>n</m> has two prime factorizations: 
      <md>
        <mrow>n \amp = p_1 p_2 \cdots p_k</mrow>
        <mrow>n \amp = q_1 q_2 \cdots q_m
      </mrow>
      </md>
      where <m>p_1, p_2, \ldots, p_k</m> and <m>q_1, q_2, \ldots, q_m</m> are prime numbers.  You want to show that <m>k=m</m> and that the sets of primes are the same (up to order).  Show that <m>p_1</m> must divide one of the <m>q_i</m>'s, up to relabelling <m>q_1</m>.  Deduce that <m>p_1 = q_1</m>.  We can then cancel <m>p_1</m> and <m>q_1</m> from both factorizations and repeat the argument to show that <m>p_2</m> must, up to relabelling, equal <m>q_2</m>, and so on.  You may find  <xref ref="definition-divisibility"/>, <xref ref="definition-prime_number"/>, <xref ref="proposition-euclid_lemma"/>, <xref ref="proposition-well_ordered_rings_have_cancellation"/> useful.
    </p>
  </proof>
</proposition>

<proposition xml:id="proposition-fundamental_theorem_of_arithmetic">
  <title>Fundamental Theorem of Arithmetic</title>
  <statement>
    <p>
      Every positive integer greater than 1 can be uniquely expressed as a product of prime numbers, up to the order of the factors.
    </p>
  </statement>
  <proof>
    <p>
      You may find  <xref ref="proposition-prime_factorization_existence"/> and <xref ref="proposition-uniqueness_of_prime_factorization"/> useful.
    </p>
  </proof>
</proposition>

</section>